title: For Sale:  Alignment washer for Daystate Regal XL, Wolverine & Air Wolf with Hugget Shroud
postcontent: Attention: All Daystate air rifle owners with Hugget Shroud installed in your rifle. Please be aware that the Hugget Shroud is not made perfectly to match the Daystate Firing tube. Reason is because the Hugget shroud’s tube is held on to the firing tube with 2 set screws at the breech area. The Hugget tube has a tendency to be cocked on an angle if your suppressor is accidentally knocked on a hard surface or rough shipment. Another reason is some Hugget shroud did not have an O-ring. This happened to me when I sent my Daystate Regal to AOA for repairs and they never test fired after the repairs. When I got it back, I went to the range and found out there were no pellets coming out, just tiny lead fragments. I sent it back again to AOA for repairs & they just installed an O-ring near the threaded portion. I’m thinking that the O-ring can wear (like the O ring in the pellet magazine w/c I replaced twice already) and eventually go back to the same problem. My solution is to make a long washer which will fit the OD of the firing tube and will fit the ID of the Hugget tube. The tolerance was extremely tight to guarantee a slip/light press fit for a zero movement 360 degrees. Now, I’m confident that the suppressor will always be aligned with the firing tube. I have my friend make 3. Sold 1 & have only one left. Once this is sold, they'll be all gone. It may fit other models like Wolverine, Air Wolf, or any other Daystate model as long as the OD of the firing tube and ID of the Hugget tube are the same as Daystate Regal XL's dimensions. (I would imagine so but check with AOA to be sure).

title: For Sale/Trade:  Dutch no. 5 Carbine w/ Rare ammo
postcontent: For sale is a Dutch 1895 Carbine in the no. 5 configuration. It is chambered in 6.5x53.5 Dutch, which can be difficult to find. This particular rifle is a converted carbine from around WWII. It was originally made in 1911 as a full length rifle at the Hembrug arsenal, and was later converted in 1940 to carbine. It is in beautiful shape and has what looks to be an untouched stock with great markings and a nice, sharp cartouche. This rifle is all matching. The stock doesn't match, but from what I understand that is normal for these converted guns. Also, the upper handguard is missing a small sliver on the part that hangs over the barrel, it also has a almost unnoticeable hairline crack on the rear portion of the handguard. The receiver is in the white, which is also correct. I have not fired this, but it looks to be in excellant mechanical condition, and has one of the smoothest bolts I have ever experienced in a milsurp. The bore is slightly dark but still has shine and great rifling. The 6.5 round it fires is also a pleasure to shoot.Comes with 229 rounds of ammo and 30 purple wood blanks. Most of the ammo looks to be steel cased, German occupation made ammo. Also includes what appears to be an original Dutch sling, and 10 en-bloc clips. Ammo can be difficult to find and often sells for $1+/round.Asking $600 for everything.

title: For Sale:  Walther PPK/S Talo Custom Ernst 009/200 - New and pristine!
postcontent: This particular firearm is number 009 of 200 and is a beauty!  The last 200 to roll off of the assembly . . .German engraver, Gustav Ernst published a series of pattern books between 1839 and 1853. Many of the now well known early American engravers like Nimschke studied Ernst's patterns while in industrial school in Germany. This style became the foundation of American firearms engraving when his students emigrated to this country.The Walther Ernst PPK/S uses a more Germanic style Ernst pattern on the slide with a centered gold deer on a stainless pistol. The safety reflects the pattern. These were the last 200 Walther PPK/S made under contract by the S&W Houlton, Maine factory. The grips are a walnut laminate with the Walther logo and a reflection of the slide design in the center. The guns are marked sequentially "xxx of 200" on the frame.
